data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has these Thread.Abort patterns:

| Pattern Found | Location |
|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` in `ProcessLoop` |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | catch block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Prevents rethrow so `finally` runs |
| **Thread.Abort()** call | `Stop()` as forced termination |
| **Blocking call** | `GetNextItem()` — won't respond to cancellation |

## Key Problems in .NET 8

- `Thread.Abort()` → throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`
- `Thread.ResetAbort()` → throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`
- `ThreadAbortException` → never thrown by the runtime

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed: we simply continue to the loop
                // condition check, which will exit the while loop.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't stop in time. With cooperative cancellation
                // this means GetNextItem/ProcessItem isn't checking the token.
                // Log a warning — there is no .NET 8 equivalent of Abort().
                Console.Error.WriteLine("Worker thread did not stop within timeout.");
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical: You Must Also Update `GetNextItem`

The original `GetNextItem()` "may block" — a `CancellationToken` won't interrupt it unless you thread it through:

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — blocking with no way to cancel except Abort
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks indefinitely
}

// AFTER (.NET 8) — cancellation-aware
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken)
                               // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, replace it too:

```csharp
// BEFORE
Thread.Sleep(1000);

// AFTER — wakes immediately on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000);
```

## Pitfalls to Watch

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing token to blocking calls** | Cancellation is *cooperative* — if `GetNextItem()` blocks without a token, `Stop()` hangs until the block releases naturally. There is no force-kill. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and registered callbacks. Always `Dispose()`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish cancellation from real errors. |
| **Expecting instant stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort` which injected an exception anywhere, cancellation only fires at checkpoints. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running. |
| **No fallback for truly uncooperative code** | If you call third-party code that can't accept a token, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only .NET 8 equivalent of a forced stop. |

## Summary of API Replacements

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Remove — just continue the loop |
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep(ms)` | `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` |

The fundamental shift: **.NET Framework could yank the rug out from under a thread**; **.NET 8 requires the thread to check and voluntarily stop**. Every blocking call in the chain must accept and honor the `CancellationToken`.
